Child and Adolescent Social Work Volume 8, Number 4, August 1991
Social Policy and Intervention with Chemically Dependent Women and Their ChiIdren
Elizabeth A. Segal, Ph.D.
ABSTRACT: The increase in drug dependency among infants has significant implications for social service providers and must be addressed on the policy level. The policy debates and legislation which have surfaced to date need to be examined more closely and considered in the context of social service needs. This article considers policy options from the framework of social needs and individual needs in relation to the problem of maternal and infant chemical dependency.
The issues of drug use, drug addiction, and drug production are not new. The use of drugs for medicinal, religious, and recreational purposes has existed for thousands of years (O'Brien & Cohen, 1984). In recent years, the non-medical use of drugs has received a great deal of attention. Controversy exists around the extent to which drug use and abuse have risen, and what those trends mean for policymakers. Data do indicate that among women of childbearing age, the use and abuse of illicit drugs have increased and it is a problem of national importance.
As has been discussed in the previous articles, the incidence, extent, and consequences of maternal drug use have increased and worsened in recent years. According to the National Institute on Drug Abuse (1989), by the age of 25, over 80% of today's young adults have tried an illicit drug. Over 5 million women of childbearing age (15-44) currently use an illicit drug. The National Drug Control Strategy reported an estimated 100,000 infants are exposed to cocaine each year, while the National Association for Perinatal Addiction Re-
