search and Education estimated as many as 375,000 infants are exposed to drugs each year (U.S. General Accounting Office, 1990b).
Some research indicates that the incidence of illicit drug abuse during pregnancy may be as high as 11% (Chasnoff, 1989). While the incidence may be high, the likelihood of diagnosis is low. Lack of early medical care and screening coupled with underreporting suggest that the problem is more prevalent than current research indicates. Social factors such as changes in gender role, occupational status, social expectations as well as risk factors such as poverty and single parenthood seem to contribute to the increase in drug use among women (Segal, 1988). Risk factors such as poor prenatal nutrition, poor prenatal care, and chaotic home conditions have been found to be linked with maternal drug abuse and have an affect on maternal responsiveness after the infant is born (Johnson & Rosen, 1990). Thus, it becomes difficult to separate the environmental stresses from the personal stresses, and to determine whether drug abuse is a symptom or a cause.
The increase in drug dependency among infants has significant implications for social service providers and must be addressed on the policy level. The policy debates and legislation which have surfaced to date need to be examined more closely and considered in the context of social service needs. This article considers policy options from the framework of social needs and individual needs in relation to the problem of maternal and infant chemical dependency.
Policy Options
There tend to be three areas of focus when discussing policy alternatives to address the problem of drug abuse: 1) enforcement and punishment, 2) treatment, and 3) education for prevention. From a policy perspective, these three options require very different legislative approaches. The direction of social services and the implications for social work practice depend on the policy approach chosen.
The enforcement and punishment approach relies on the incarceration of those who produce, supply, sell, and/or consume illegal substances. The goal is to eradicate both those who are involved and the substances and thereby put an end to the problem. In 1987, the United Nations International Conference on Drug Abuse and Illicit Trafficking was held with 138 nations participating. Their goal was to better coordinate anti-drug activities world-wide (General Account-

ELIZABETH A. SEGAL 287
ing Office, 1990a). The Conference revealed that unlike many other nations, United States efforts include use of the military for the interdiction of drugs in producing nations as well as coming into this country. This approach is reflected in the common terminology used, that we are "fighting a drug war." While enforcement and control of illegal drugs are important, this approach to fighting a war necessitates an enforcer and an enemy, and thus overshadows the other policy alternatives.
Treatment of drug users takes a different approach. When treating people who are addicted to drugs, a medical model is often reflected. There are no enforcers and enemies, but rather those who can help and those in need of service. The medical model for treatment reflects the belief that drug addiction is a disease, and can therefore be "cured" by medical professionals. By placing drug abuse as a disease to be diagnosed and treated, we "shift the emphasis from social and cultural to individual causes and cures" (Peele, 1989, p. 243). The result is that emphasis is placed on making individual change rather than examining and questioning the impact of social surroundings.
However, evidence suggests that treatment programs can help women to overcome their addiction to drugs (U.S. House Select Committee on Children, Youth, and Families, 1990b). Case management programs have been found to be particularly beneficial. Case managers can go into communities and help to link drug dependent women to services which may include pre or postnatal care, transportation, child care, or job training, in addition to substance abuse treatment services (Atkins, 1990).
The third approach stresses prevention. Through means such as education and public awareness campaigns, emphasis is placed on educating people about the negative consequences of drug use and possibly offering alternative ways of dealing with precipitators to drug use. Prevention can encourage closer examination of how social surroundings influence drug abuse, or it can rely on scare tactics such as those often seen in the media which portray the deadly side effects of drugs.
The direction of social policy and social services depends on which of these three approaches one holds. This is particularly true when discussing maternal use of illicit drugs where there is an alleged "willing" user, the mother, and an alleged "innocent and powerless" user, the infant. The approach which seems appropriate for dealing with the abusing mother may not be advantageous to the child, and vice versa. For example, punishing the mother by removing her child

