Public Policy Initiatives
The recent increase in public interest has sparked much debate and prompted policy makers to take action. The most comprehensive effort to address the problem of drug abuse was put into law in November of 1988 through the "Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1988" (P.L. 100-690). While receiving a great deal of publicity as the "war on drugs", the 1988 Act represents an extension of previous federal efforts in dealing with the problem of drug abuse in this country.
The first federal law to control the use of nonmedical drugs was passed as early as 1887 (Hogan & Doyle, 1989). This legislation prohibited the importing of opium into the United States. As is true of many social policies, the control of illegal drugs has been undertaken predominantly by the Federal government. Early efforts were primarily aimed at import control and then expanded to include national restrictions. Provisions for treatment through federal legislation first appeared as part of the Community Mental Health Centers Act of 1963 (P.L. 88-164).
The Comprehensive Crime Control Act of 1984 (P.L. 98-473) included provisions for drug enforcement. It authorized the detention of drug dealers for preventive reasons and introduced more severe penalties for drug trafficking offenses. In terms of policy approaches, it can be characterized as falling under efforts at incarceration and punishment.
In 1986, the Anti-Drug Abuse Act (P.O. 99-570) combined enforcement strategies with treatment efforts. This legislation authorized expanded efforts at enforcement in drug-producing countries, strengthened interdiction efforts and antismuggling provisions, increased criminal sanctions against drug offenders, and authorized increased funding for drug treatment and rehabilitation. The majority of the authorized funding was for law enforcement.
The Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1988 represents the current strategy endorsed by policy makers. The bill is very comprehensive and includes:

ELIZABETH A. SEGAL 289
1. establishment of the Office of National Drug Control Policy and creation of the national "drug czar" to serve at the Cabinet level,
2. increases in treatment and prevention programs, 3. international narcotics control efforts, 4. increases criminal penalties, 5. death penalty for major drug traffickers, and 6. stiffer penalties for drug dealers.
The comprehensive nature of the bill acknowledges the complexity of the problem of drug abuse and the wide spread social dimensions. While this breadth of coverage reflects the reality of drug usage, it also presents a potential implementation and coordination nightmare. The legislation includes efforts by eight cabinet departments (Justice, Interior, Health and Human Services, Labor, Education, Treasury, Housing and Urban Development, and Veterans Affairs), the Executive Office of the President, the FBI, the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms, and numerous other federal offices. Coordination of these efforts is to be run under the newly created Office of National Drug Control Policy. While it is too early to assess the success of this office, the organization of so many high level offices is at best extremely difficult. Already within a year of its implementation, there has been a turnover in the director position bringing to question the stability of the office.
While this bill authorized $5.5 billion to be spent, only $3.7 billion or about 2/3's of the outlined funding was actually committed (Congressional Quarterly Almanac, 1989). Herein lies one of the most frustrating aspects of federal legislative initiatives. While a great deal of publicity surrounds the passage of legislation, little is heard publicly when the actual dollars are committed through federal legislative budgeting.
Of the funds authorized through the 1988 federal legislation, the majority of dollars have been committed to the enforcement and interdiction efforts (U.S. House Select Committee on Children, Youth, & Families, 1990a). In FY 1989, 72% of the funds were earmarked for criminal justice, international control, interdiction, and intelligence. Estimates for FY 1990 and FY 1991 place 71% of these funds set aside for these efforts. Overall, about one fourth of the money authorized by the federal government to deal with the problem of drug abuse is for treatment, education, community services and prevention. Within these treatment funds, about $500 million is for the A1-

