cohol and Drug Abuse and Mental Health services Block Grant. Ten percent of the $500 million must be set aside for programs and services designed for women, particularly pregnant women and women with dependent children (Wilson, 1989). Although this is an increase from original set-asides outlined in 1984, it represents a small federal effort in relation to the need.
Thus, while federal policy has expanded in response to the problem of drug abuse, the provisions directed toward the issue of maternal and infant drug dependence represent less than 1% of the total dollars authorized by the 1988 Act. This minuscule amount reflects the federal priority directed towards the problem of women, infants, and drug dependence.
Treatment Efforts
Although there have been earmarked funds to serve women since 1984, the commitment to create and expand programs designed for women has been minimal (Galbraith, 1990). Drug treatment is virtually nonexistent for pregnant women (Fink, 1989). For example, in Michigan, there are 16 licensed programs that provide treatment services for women, but only one serves pregnant drug dependent women in particular (Walker, 1990). Of these programs that do provide services to pregnant women,most have long waiting lists. Of the pregnant women nationwide in need of drug treatment, the National Association of State Alcohol and Drug Abuse Directors estimates that less than 11% receive care (U.S. General Accounting Office, 1990b).
In addition to the inadequate supply of services, a number of barriers act to inhibit the use of those treatment opportunities which do exist. Many drug treatment providers fear the potential liability in serving pregnant women. There is concern about the potential for complications when using medications for treatment, and from the lack of prenatal care. Clinics could be held responsible for consequences suffered by the infant while the mother is being treated. Another basic issue for some women is the need for child care. If there are other children in the family, the lack of child care makes it difficult for a woman to participate in treatment services.
Enforcement Efforts
Pregnant women are reluctant to seek treatment, even when available. There is a growing fear of criminal prosecution if a pregnant woman co,nes forward and makes public her addiction to illegal drugs. Officials at all levels of government have moved towards im-

ELIZABETH A. SEGAL 291
plementing more punitive measures against pregnant women who use drugs. These measures include criminalizing drug use during pregnancy and taking custody of newborns who test positive for drugs at birth (Smith, 1990).
The ACLU found that six states have already changed their definition of "neglect" so that infants with controlled substances in their systems at birth are included, and three other states have legislation pending. Hundreds of pregnant women have been charged for child abuse. Over 30 women have been criminally charged for using drugs while pregnant and thus delivering drugs to a minor (U.S. House Select Committee on Children, Youth, and Families, 1990b). These enforcement directions raise a number of concerns regarding civil liberties and open the door to questions of what behaviors by pregnant women are subject to public punishment. Does the drinking of a glass of wine during pregnancy become classified as abusive? Is excessive exercise potentially dangerous to the fetus and thus considered abuse? Not only does this raise questions about what is abuse and neglect, but it helps to ensure that pregnant women who do have a drug problem will not come forward for fear of criminal prosecution and loss of custody of their child.
Education and Prevention
One way to minimize the consequences of drug abuse is to prevent people from becoming addicted in the first place. Prevention is included as part of our current federal policy, but the emphasis is on deterrence through law enforcement. The approach is that if the penalties are high, then a person will not choose to use drugs. This perspective, like the medical model, ignores other variables, such as environmental factors, which contribute to drug use.
Evaluations of programs which stress the terrible consequences of using drugs indicate that they have little or no impact on drug use (Klebe, 1989). Drug information programs alone do not seem to be effective. Rather, programs which promote self-esteem, stress management, and communication skills in addition to providing accurate information seem to have better results.
Implications for Social Work
The growing problem of chemical dependence among women and infants has tremendous ramifications for our social service system. The

292 CHILD AND ADOLESCENT SOCIAL WORK
social service areas most likely to feel the strain are the child welfare, medical, and educational systems. An increase in the incidence of child abuse and neglect cases can be traced in part to the greater use of drugs. In New York City, cases tripled between 1986 and 1988 and officials identified drugs as a major factor in the increase (Children's Defense Fund, 1990). These changes mean more investigations and cases for an already troubled child welfare system.
In addition to cases of abuse and neglect, a growth in foster care is also attributed in part to the increase in drug abuse. From 1986 to 1989, foster care placements increased by almost 29% nationwide (Besharov, 1990). Over half of the increase is concentrated in two states, California and New York. These two states have been particularly hard hit by crack addiction and insufficient services. The number of drug-exposed infants referred by hospitals to child welfare authorities from 1986 to 1989 rose significantly. In New York, referrals rose by 268%, in Los Angeles by 342%, and in Chicago by 1,735% (U.S. General Accounting Office, 1990b). This phenomenon has given rise to the problem of "boarder babies," infants who remain in a hospital for nonmedical reasons. Foster homes for chemically exposed infants are difficult to find, and often the hospital becomes the only place available for care. Hospitals are becoming providers of child welfare services without additional resources and the appropriate facilities for such care.
Keeping a newborn infant in a hospital for longer periods becomes very costly. Also, drug exposed infants often are in need of intensive care and medical treatment, and this can be very costly. The cost of hospital delivery, perinatal care, and foster care through age 5 is estimated to cost more than $55,000 per child born dependent on cocaine (Office of the Inspector General, 1990). This does not include the potential costs for developmental intervention, education and health care. The first five years of life for a child born drug dependent can cost the social service system well over $225,000. For systems already financially constrained, the increase in the number of babies born to drug addicted mothers will be very costly in the future.
Social Policy Agenda
Current social policy has focused the majority of resources and attention on the enforcement and punishment aspects of controlling drug use. Critics argue that this approach has failed. Although drug enforcement has been the central federal effort, more drugs are avail-

ELIZABETH A. SEGAL 293
able at cheaper prices, and in fact, U.S. enforcement agencies have stopped only 3-10% of the illegal drugs which enter the country (Moore, 1989). Punitive legal measures will keep pregnant women from using prenatal services and deter them from participating in treatment programs. The fear of liability and insufficient resources continue to limit the availability of services for pregnant women. Continued emphasis on the medical model of treatment which does not address the environmental variables which are related to the use of illicit drugs will perpetuate a focus on symptoms and not cause.
It is crucial that we examine our attitudes and hence approach to dealing with the problem of drug abuse and infants born chemically exposed. The adversarial stance of drug enforcement makes pregnant women and ultimately their babies enemies of the public welfare. Yet, in the end the social welfare system is called to step in and care for the child. The services needed to help a chemical exposed infant are costly and the potential for successful outcomes is poor. A policy approach which is more preventive and less punitive is needed in order to better serve the growing number of babies born to drug using mothers. Such a policy should address the three areas of policy:
