9 Educational materials which are designed for those at greatest risk,
9 Teams of specialists trained to do outreach and education to work with community residents to train them to become educators,
9 Education programs which are not sensationalist and include efforts to enhance self-esteem and training to promote better stress management, communication skills, and ways to deal with outside social pressures.
9 Resources to create employment and educational opportunities for people living in high risk communities.
The incidence of drug dependent babies is unlikely to disappear in the near future. The cost of caring for these children is high and is taxing our already strained social welfare system. Measures which reach women early and provide care and support have a better likelihood of creating a positive intervention. Overall, it is also extremely important to remember the social factors which contribute to the abuse of drugs. Lack of economic opportunity, social isolation, poor education, and poverty all contribute to making the use and selling of drugs attractive. These social concerns must also be addressed if headway is to be gained in decreasing the incidence of drug abuse in this country.
